From: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
Subject: [PATCH] ASoC: tas571x: TAS5713 (steelhead) master volume scale — no PA software boost

The TAS5713 shares tas5711_controls, whose Master volume dB scale tops out at
+24 dB digital gain, so PulseAudio's 100% sat above the hardware max: the Master
control saturated ~PA 45% and PA added software gain above that (dead zone + a
software boost that hurts quality; the desktop icon read 45% at the real max).

Give the TAS5713 its own controls whose MASTER uses a scale shifted down 24 dB so
the hardware max register maps to PA 0 dB / 100% (PA spreads 0-100% across the
Master control, no software boost, icon reads full at the ceiling, hardware
volume throughout). The per-channel Speaker volume KEEPS the original scale: PA
pins it at its "0 dB" point and a shifted scale would pin it at the +24 dB
extreme, stacking a second +24 dB on Master (measured +48 dB at PA 100%).

Signed-off-by: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
---
 sound/soc/codecs/tas571x.c | 28 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 26 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

--- a/sound/soc/codecs/tas571x.c	2026-07-08 14:54:06.586221433 +0200
+++ b/sound/soc/codecs/tas571x.c	2026-07-08 14:54:06.594445267 +0200
@@ -785,11 +785,39 @@
 	.vol_reg_size			= 1,
 };
 
+/* Nexus Q (steelhead): the TAS5713 master volume tops out at a large digital
+ * gain, so PulseAudio's 100% sat well above the hardware maximum -- the Master
+ * control saturated around PA 45% and PA added SOFTWARE gain above that (a dead
+ * zone in the top half of the slider + a software boost that hurts quality and
+ * made the desktop volume icon read 45% at the real max). Give the TAS5713 its
+ * own Master dB scale shifted so the hardware maximum register (0xff) maps to
+ * PA 0 dB (== PA 100%): PA then spreads its whole 0-100% across the Master
+ * control with NO software boost, the icon reads full at the real ceiling, and
+ * volume stays hardware/decibel the whole way. The per-channel Speaker volume
+ * MUST keep the original scale: PA pins it at its "0 dB" point, and shifting it
+ * too would pin it at the register's +24 dB extreme, stacking a second +24 dB
+ * on Master (measured +48 dB total at PA 100%). Original scale -> unity. */
+static const DECLARE_TLV_DB_SCALE(tas5713_volume_tlv, -12750, 50, 1);
+
+static const struct snd_kcontrol_new tas5713_controls[] = {
+	SOC_SINGLE_TLV("Master Volume",
+		       TAS571X_MVOL_REG,
+		       0, 0xff, 1, tas5713_volume_tlv),
+	SOC_DOUBLE_R_TLV("Speaker Volume",
+			 TAS571X_CH1_VOL_REG,
+			 TAS571X_CH2_VOL_REG,
+			 0, 0xff, 1, tas5711_volume_tlv),
+	SOC_DOUBLE("Speaker Switch",
+		   TAS571X_SOFT_MUTE_REG,
+		   TAS571X_SOFT_MUTE_CH1_SHIFT, TAS571X_SOFT_MUTE_CH2_SHIFT,
+		   1, 1),
+};
+
 static const struct tas571x_chip tas5713_chip = {
 	.supply_names			= tas5711_supply_names,
 	.num_supply_names		= ARRAY_SIZE(tas5711_supply_names),
-	.controls			= tas5711_controls,
-	.num_controls			= ARRAY_SIZE(tas5711_controls),
+	.controls			= tas5713_controls,
+	.num_controls			= ARRAY_SIZE(tas5713_controls),
 	.regmap_config			= &tas5711_regmap_config,
 	.vol_reg_size			= 1,
 };
